{% extends 'base.html.twig' %}
{% set nav = 'home' %}

{% block title %}Robinson Huron Treaty Members' Transparency Circle{% endblock %}
{% block description %}A member-led circle of beneficiaries across the Robinson Huron Treaty First Nations, asking clear, respectful questions about how our shared settlement is governed and how each community administers its share.{% endblock %}

{% block hero %}
<section class="hero">
  <div class="wrap wrap--wide">
    <p class="eyebrow">A member-led invitation across our treaty</p>
    <h1>Seeing how our settlement is governed is our right.</h1>
    <p class="lead">We are members and beneficiaries from across the Robinson Huron Treaty First Nations, organizing as one voice to understand how our shared settlement is governed and how each community administers its share.</p>
    <p class="lead">One question sits at the centre: when our settlement funds are held and invested, what are the rules, who decides, and what are members entitled to see?</p>
  </div>
</section>
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <h2>Why we are doing this</h2>
  <p>In 2023 the Robinson Huron Treaty First Nations reached a ten billion dollar settlement for unpaid annuities, covering all 21 signatory communities. The money has flowed to the communities. Many members across the treaty have said the same thing: we do not yet have a clear picture of how the funds are governed, what the rules are, or what we are entitled to see.</p>
  <p>These concerns are already public and widely shared. This Circle exists to turn that shared concern into clear, respectful, member-led questions.</p>

  <div class="card card--magenta">
    <h3>What we are, and are not</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>We are members and beneficiaries, organizing across communities as one voice.</li>
      <li>We are independent. We are not a band council committee, and we are not part of the Robinson Huron Treaty Litigation Fund or any community's administration.</li>
      <li>We are non-partisan. This is about transparency and member information, not about removing or attacking any leader.</li>
      <li>We work from sourced facts and we ask questions. We do not make accusations.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>What we are asking for</h2>
  <p>Two levels, one standard:</p>

  <div class="standard-part">
    <p class="eyebrow">Treaty-wide</p>
    <p>From the Robinson Huron Treaty Litigation Fund: the compensation and disbursement agreement, the list of trustees and how they are chosen, the rules for amending the agreement, and what reporting beneficiaries are entitled to receive.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="standard-part">
    <p class="eyebrow">Community level</p>
    <p>A shared set of questions that members in any community can put to their own council about its settlement trust: who holds the funds, the trust's governing rules, what the funds can be invested in, who can authorize a withdrawal, and how the held funds reconcile to the audited statements.</p>
  </div>

  <p>The aim is a common transparency standard every community's members can use, so no one is asking alone.</p>

  <div class="btn-row">
    <a class="btn" href="/standard">Read the shared standard</a>
    <a class="btn btn--alt" href="/get-involved">Get involved</a>
  </div>

  <h2>How to take part</h2>
  <p>Any beneficiary who shares these principles can take part. The idea is simple: bring one or two members from your community who are willing to be a local contact, and use the shared standard so every community is asking the same plain questions in the same respectful way.</p>
{% endblock %}
